  "prompt": "What is the heaviest weight ever lifted by a human being?",
  "response": "The title of the \"heaviest weight ever lifted by a human being\" varies depending on the type of lift, the equipment used, and the context of the lift (e.g., competition versus demonstration). Below are some of the most notable and officially recognized records across different lifting disciplines:\n\n### **1. Deadlift**\n\n- **Heaviest **Raw** Deadlift:**\n  - **501 kg (1,104 lbs)** by **Haf\u00fe\u00f3r J\u00fal\u00edus Bj\u00f6rnsson** (Iceland)  \n    - Achieved on **May 2, 2020**, during the World's Ultimate Strongman Feats of Strength event.\n    - **Raw deadlift** refers to lifting without specialized supportive equipment like deadlift suits.\n\n- **Heaviest **Equipped** Deadlift:**\n  - **525 kg (1,157 lbs)** by **Benedikt Magn\u00fasson** (Iceland)  \n    - Accomplished on **May 2, 2011**.\n    - **Equipped deadlift** allows the use of supportive gear such as deadlift suits and straps, which can help lift greater weights.\n\n### **2. Olympic Weightlifting**\n\nOlympic weightlifting consists of two main lifts: the **snatch** and the **clean and jerk**.\n\n- **Heaviest Snatch:**\n  - **222 kg (489 lbs)** by **Lasha Talakhadze** (Georgia)  \n    - Set at the **2021 World Weightlifting Championships**.\n\n- **Heaviest Clean and Jerk:**\n  - **264 kg (582 lbs)** by **Lasha Talakhadze** (Georgia)  \n    - Also achieved at the **2021 World Weightlifting Championships**.\n  \n- **Combined Total:**\n  - **485 kg (1,070 lbs)** by **Lasha Talakhadze**  \n    - This is the sum of his snatch and clean and jerk lifts, making it the highest combined total in Olympic weightlifting history.\n\n### **3. Powerlifting**\n\nPowerlifting focuses on three main lifts: the **squat**, **bench press**, and **deadlift**.\n\n- **Heaviest **Raw** Deadlift:**\n  - **501 kg (1,104 lbs)** by **Haf\u00fe\u00f3r J\u00fal\u00edus Bj\u00f6rnsson**  \n    - Matches his strongman deadlift record.\n\n- **Heaviest **Equipped** Bench Press:**\n  - **335 kg (738.5 lbs)** by **Will Barotti** (United States)  \n    - Achieved on **September 17, 2023**.\n  \n- **Heaviest **Raw** Bench Press:**\n  - **355 kg (782.6 lbs)** by **Jimmy Kolb** (United States)  \n    - Set on **June 19, 2023**.\n\n### **4. Strongman Lifts**\n\nStrongman competitions often feature unconventional lifts, and some of the heaviest lifts are achieved in this context.\n\n- **Atlas Stones:**\n  - Athletes lift heavy spherical stones onto platforms of varying heights. The weights of these stones can exceed **200 kg (440 lbs)** each.\n\n- **Husafell Stone:**\n  - While not a lift in the traditional sense, carrying or lifting large stones like the **Husafell Stone** (around **186 kg or more**) is a common strongman feat.\n\n### **5. Historical Claims**\n\nSome historical figures are reputed to have lifted extraordinary weights, though these claims lack the rigorous documentation and verification standards of modern competitions.\n\n- **Louis Cyr (Canada):**\n  - Allegedly backlifted **4,337 kg (9,570 lbs)**, but such claims are considered legendary and not substantiated by contemporary records.\n\n- **Paul Anderson (United States):**\n  - Reported a backlift of **6,270 kg (13,800 lbs)**, though this is not officially recognized in competitive settings.\n\n### **Notes on Equipment and Categories**\n\n- **Raw vs. Equipped:**  \n  - **Raw lifting** refers to performing lifts without supportive or enhancing equipment, relying solely on human strength.\n  - **Equipped lifting** allows the use of specialized gear like bench press shirts, squat suits, and deadlift suits, which can significantly increase the amount of weight a person can lift.\n\n- **Verification and Competition Standards:**  \n  - Official records are typically set in sanctioned competitions with strict rules and verification processes to ensure legitimacy and consistency.\n\n### **Conclusion**\n\nAs of my knowledge cutoff in October 2023, **Haf\u00fe\u00f3r J\u00fal\u00edus Bj\u00f6rnsson's** 501 kg deadlift stands out as one of the heaviest officially recognized lifts in the realm of strength sports. In Olympic weightlifting, **Lasha Talakhadze** holds the record for the highest combined total. It's important to consider the context and the type of lift when discussing the heaviest weights lifted by humans.",
